observations.recommendation:
The Municipal Mayor and other concerned officials ensure completeness of the conduct of physical count of PPE and Investment Property with the end in view of rendering a complete RPCPPE;

The Municipal Mayor and other concerned officials initiate steps to ensure that property and accounting records are fully reconciled;

The Municipal Mayor and other concerned officials determine the status of ownership of all land, building and other specific assets noted and submit to the Audit Team their ownership status, and on whether such assets are recorded in the books, including a written explanation on the deficiencies noted; 

The Municipal Mayor and other concerned officials include at least one regular staff from the Accounting Unit as a member of the Inventory Committee pursuant to Item 5.2 of COA Circular No. 2020-006; and

The Municipal Mayor and other concerned officials initiate steps towards the application of the one-time cleansing of PPE account balances in accordance with COA Circular No. 2020-006.

The Municipal Accountant revises the Local Road Networks Ledger Card with the template as prescribed in Annex D of COA Circular No. 2015-008;

The Municipal Accountant revises the Notes to the Financial Statements taking into consideration the additional disclosure on local road networks as required in Annex B of COA Circular No. 2015-008; and

The Municipal Accountant ensures that subsequent presentation of disclosure on PPE be properly presented with the data requirements as required in Annex G of COA Circular No. 2016-004.

The Municipal Treasurer and the Supply Officer initiate steps in segregating items below the capitalization threshold and make a separate monitoring of these items apart from PPE; 

The Municipal Treasurer and the Supply Officer initiate steps in the assignment of property numbers following the numbering system as prescribed in Item 5.6 of COA Circular No. 2020-006;

The Municipal Treasurer and the Supply Officer coordinate with the Municipal Accountant towards assignment of unit values based on actual costs;


The Municipal Treasurer and the Supply Officer initiate steps in the identification and whereabouts of accountable officers for items not found during the physical count for proper demand of items under their accountability or recovery of equivalent value thereof; 

The Municipal Treasurer and the Supply Officer establish controls so that accountable officers from other government agencies are fully settled with their property accountabilities before reassignment to outside the LGU jurisdiction to decrease difficulty of recovery of the property under their accountability;

The Municipal Treasurer and the Supply Officer ensure that all properties are attached with property stickers complete with the necessary information pertaining to the PPE item in accordance with Item 5.7 of COA Circular No. 2020-006;

The Municipal Treasurer and the Supply Officer submit a written justification on the erroneous reporting of unserviceable properties of some PPE items as serviceable in the RPCPPE; and

The Municipal Treasurer and the Supply Officer expedite the preparation and maintenance of a complete set of Property Cards.

The Municipal Mayor ensures that the Municipal Accountant submit subsequent disbursement vouchers for confidential fund cash advances to the Audit Team within the deadline set in Section 6.1.8.4 of the Joint Circular;

The Municipal Mayor ensures that subsequent liquidation reports for quarterly cash advances be submitted to the ICFAU within the deadline set in Section 6.2.2 of the Joint Circular; and

The Municipal Mayor submits to the ICFAU a copy of the duly acknowledged transmittal letter of the liquidation report pertaining to the dormant confidential fund cash advance amounting to ₱600,000.00 to facilitate closing thereof in the books.

The Municipal Treasurer causes the immediate remittance of deficient shares of RPT collections to barangays totaling ₱168,892.28;

The Municipal Treasurer releases the shares of RPT collections to barangays in accordance with Section 271 of RA No. 7160; and

The Municipal Treasurer requires all deputized barangay treasurers to fully remit all community tax collections and subsequently issue checks to barangays for the release of their respective shares in these collections.

The Municipal Mayor and other concerned officials initiates steps towards the revision of the plantilla of personnel taking into consideration the additional manpower needs of all departments and offices of the Municipality; 

The Municipal Mayor instructs the HRMO to initiate steps towards the filling-in of existing vacancies based on the revised plantilla, with the end in view of maximizing the organizational structure; 

The Municipal Mayor and other concerned officials hire casual personnel in accordance with the provisions of Section 9.g of the revised 2017 ORAOHRA;

The Municipal Mayor and other concerned officials hire Job Order workers only for the purpose of implementing local projects in accordance with Section 77 of RA No. 7160; and

The Municipal Mayor considers designating personnel in accordance with the revised 2017 ORAOHRA.

The Municipal Mayor ceases the designation of Job Order and casual personnel as revenue collectors; 

The Municipal Mayor directs the Municipal Treasurer to determine the total manpower needs of his Office especially on the total additional revenue collectors; 

The Municipal Mayor initiates steps towards the revision of the approved plantilla of personnel taking into consideration the manpower needs of the Office of the Municipal Treasurer; and

The Municipal Mayor directs the HRMO to initiate steps towards the hiring, reassignment and transfer of personnel to fill-in the vacant positions of the treasury office in accordance with civil service rules and in compliance with DBM LBC No. 137.

Municipal General Services Officer prepare separate property cards on all classes of PPE as prescribed in the Manual on NGAS for LGUs;

Municipal Accountant maintain separate ledger cards of all PPE accounts; and


Municipality’s Inventory Committee conduct the annual physical count for all PPEs, to prepare the RPCPPE and to submit the same to the Audit Team for evaluation not later than January 31 of each year.

Municipal Accountant to:

Prepare and maintain subsidiary ledgers and lapsing schedule for depreciation expenses accounts pursuant to Section 111 of Presidential Decree No. 1445 and IPSAS No. 17;

Ensure that PPE accounts are reconciled with the amounts indicated in the PPE lapsing schedule.

Municipal Accountant investigate and determine the nature and particulars of the long-outstanding unliquidated cash advances totaling ₱6,963,140.00;

Municipal Accountant issue demand letters to the concerned accountable officers on the immediate liquidation of these unliquidated cash advances; and 

Accountable officers submit the liquidation documents to the Municipal Accountant and refund unexpended balances, if any.  Otherwise, it is enjoined that the Municipal Accountant and other concerned officials cause the withholding of their salaries until all advances are fully liquidated.

Municipal Mayor to issue a memorandum with appropriate timelines in requiring the Municipal Treasurer, in coordination with the Municipal Assessor, for the prompt updating of the RPTAR and preparation of the duly certified list of real property tax collectibles per taxpayer for submission to the Municipal Accountant so as to resolve this recurring audit observation;

Municipal Accountant to:

Establish its accruals at the beginning of the year based on the certified list of collectibles on real property taxes as furnished by the Municipal Treasurer in compliance with Section 20 of the Manual on NGAS for LGUs, IPSAS 1 and P.D. No. 1445; 

Investigate/trace the unreconciled differences, take appropriate actions by providing adjusting entries and monitor these accounts in order to prevent further discrepancies.  A copy of the adjusting entries, if any, shall be furnished to the Audit Team, for evaluation; and

Maintain the subsidiary ledgers of SET and RPT Receivables accounts including its corresponding Deferred SET and RPT accounts.

We recommended and Management agreed through the Municipal Accountant to:
Set up the Receivables- Disallowances/ Charges account every time there is an issuance of Notice of Finality of Decision for Notice of Disallowances and prepare a separate Subsidiary Ledger for each person liable for proper monitoring;
Prepare the necessary adjusting journal entries to correct the erroneous recording of the partial settlements as proposed below:

We recommended and Management:
Through the Municipal Accountant, agreed to submit to the Audit Team the lacking disbursement vouchers and the corresponding supporting documents for evaluation;
Agreed to ensure that the approval/authorization from the Sanggunian pertaining to the expenditures in the generic appropriation were included in the submission;
Through the Municipal Budget Officer, agreed to stop the practice of implementing generic or lump-sum appropriations on the identified development projects unless further approved and authorized by the Sanggunian; and
Through the Municipal Development Council in coordination with the Municipal Budget Officer, agreed to specify the details of the identified priority projects to be charged against the 20% DF which shall include, among others, project location, specific project/program description and specific implementation schedule.

The Municipal Mayor confers with the PCW, the DILG, or other government authorities on the availability of capability trainings as required in Item 4.1(A)(3) of PCW-DILG-DBM-NEDA JMC No. 2013-01, as amended;


The Municipal Mayor appropriates sufficient funds towards these capability-building programs; and


The Municipal Mayor requires all elected officials and department heads to attend all of the required capability building programs with the end in view of applying such capabilities towards the effective discharge and implementation of the Magna Carta of Women.

Provide justification on the continued performance of duties and functions as Accountable Officers despite the insufficiency of their bonding requirements against their total cash accountabilities;

Strictly comply with item 6.1.3 of COA-DBM-DILG-GCG-DND Joint Circular No. 2015-01 pertaining to the amount of cash advance to be granted to the Special Disbursing Officer on Confidential Fund;

Re-evaluate its existing cash requirements and henceforth, ensure compliance with the provisions of the fidelity bond requirement either by increasing the amount of bond of its disbursing officer or by assigning to other accountable officer the excess accountability under a separate fidelity bonding requirement as deemed appropriate.

Provide explanation as to why the unexpended balance of the current year’s LDRRMF-MOOE and QRF were not yet transferred to a Special Trust Fund under the Trust Liability-DRRMF account in its Trust Fund Books; 

Transfer the unexpended current year’s LDRRMF totalling ₱7,955,685.70 to the Special Trust Fund and accordingly recognize the related Trust Liability-DRRMF account; and

Make the necessary revisions in its financial statements taking into consideration the effects of the transfer of these unexpended current year’s LDRRMF balances.

We recommended and the Municipal Accountant agreed to:
Prepare and maintain subsidiary ledgers and lapsing schedule for depreciation expenses accounts pursuant to Section 111 of Presidential Decree No. 1445 and IPSAS No. 17;
Ensure that PPE accounts are reconciled with the amounts indicated in the PPE lapsing schedule.

We recommended that Management:
Provide justification on the continued performance of duties and functions as Accountable Officers despite the insufficiency of their bonding requirements against their total cash accountabilities;
Strictly comply with item 6.1.3 of COA-DBM-DILG-GCG-DND Joint Circular No. 2015-01 pertaining to the amount of cash advance to be granted to the Special Disbursing Officer on Confidential Fund;
Re-evaluate its existing cash requirements and henceforth, ensure compliance with the provisions of the fidelity bond requirement either by increasing the amount of bond of its disbursing officer or by assigning to other accountable officer the excess accountability under a separate fidelity bonding requirement as deemed appropriate.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor and other concerned officials:
Ensure completeness of the conduct of physical count of PPE and Investment Property with the end in view of rendering a complete RPCPPE;
Initiate steps to ensure that property and accounting records are fully reconciled;
Determine the status of ownership of all land, building and other specific assets noted and submit to the Audit Team their ownership status, and on whether such assets are recorded in the books, including a written explanation on the deficiencies noted;
Include at least one regular staff from the Accounting Unit as a member of the Inventory Committee pursuant to Item 5.2 of COA Circular No. 2020-006; and
Initiate steps towards the application of the one-time cleansing of PPE account balances in accordance with COA Circular No. 2020-006.
We also recommended that the Municipal Accountant:
Revise the Local Road Networks Ledger Card with the template as prescribed in Annex D of COA Circular No. 2015-008;
Revise the Notes to the Financial Statements taking into consideration the additional disclosure on local road networks as required in Annex B of COA Circular No. 2015-008; and
Ensure that subsequent presentation of disclosure on PPE be properly presented with the data requirements as required in Annex G of COA Circular No. 2016-004.
Lastly, we recommended and the Municipal Treasurer and the Supply Officer agreed to:
Initiate steps in segregating items below the capitalization threshold and make a separate monitoring of these items apart from PPE;
Initiate steps in the assignment of property numbers following the numbering system as prescribed in Item 5.6 of COA Circular No. 2020-006;
Coordinate with the Municipal Accountant towards assignment of unit values based on actual costs;
Initiate steps in the identification and whereabouts of accountable officers for items not found during the physical count for proper demand of items under their accountability or recovery of equivalent value thereof;
Establish controls so that accountable officers from other government agencies are fully settled with their property accountabilities before reassignment to outside the LGU jurisdiction to decrease difficulty of recovery of the property under their accountability;
Ensure that all properties are attached with property stickers complete with the necessary information pertaining to the PPE item in accordance with Item 5.7 of COA Circular No. 2020-006;
Submit a written justification on the erroneous reporting of unserviceable properties of some PPE items as serviceable in the RPCPPE; and
Expedite the preparation and maintenance of a complete set of Property Cards.

We recommended that Management:
Initiate steps towards the revision of the plantilla of personnel taking into consideration the additional manpower needs of all departments and offices of the Municipality;
Instruct the HRMO to initiate steps towards the filling-in of existing vacancies based on the revised plantilla, with the end in view of maximizing the organizational structure;
Hire casual personnel in accordance with the provisions of Section 9.g of the revised 2017 ORAOHRA;
Hire Job Order workers only for the purpose of implementing local projects in accordance with Section 77 of RA No. 7160; and
Consider designating personnel in accordance with the revised 2017 ORAOHRA.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:
Cease the designation of Job Order and casual personnel as revenue collectors;
Direct the Municipal Treasurer to determine the total manpower needs of his Office especially on the total additional revenue collectors;
Initiate steps towards the revision of the approved plantilla of personnel taking into consideration the manpower needs of the Office of the Municipal Treasurer; and
Direct the HRMO to initiate steps towards the hiring, reassignment and transfer of personnel to fill-in the vacant positions of the treasury office in accordance with civil service rules and in compliance with DBM LBC No. 137.

We recommended and the Municipal Accountant agreed to:
Prepare and maintain subsidiary ledgers and lapsing schedule for depreciation expenses accounts pursuant to Section 111 of Presidential Decree No. 1445 and IPSAS No. 17;
Ensure that PPE accounts are reconciled with the amounts indicated in the PPE lapsing schedule.

We recommended that Management:
Provide justification on the continued performance of duties and functions as Accountable Officers despite the insufficiency of their bonding requirements against their total cash accountabilities;
Strictly comply with item 6.1.3 of COA-DBM-DILG-GCG-DND Joint Circular No. 2015-01 pertaining to the amount of cash advance to be granted to the Special Disbursing Officer on Confidential Fund;
Re-evaluate its existing cash requirements and henceforth, ensure compliance with the provisions of the fidelity bond requirement either by increasing the amount of bond of its disbursing officer or by assigning to other accountable officer the excess accountability under a separate fidelity bonding requirement as deemed appropriate.
The Municipal Treasurer explained that the bond premiums of the Municipal Mayor and the Disbursing Officer were subsequently increased.
The Audit Team requests submission of their approved fidelity bonds as proof of compliance on this noted deficiency.

We recommended and the Municipal Mayor agreed to issue a memorandum with appropriate timelines in requiring the Municipal Treasurer, in coordination with the Municipal Assessor, for the prompt updating of the RPTAR and preparation of the duly certified list of real property tax collectibles per taxpayer for submission to the Municipal Accountant so as to resolve this recurring audit observation;
We also recommended and the Municipal Accountant agreed to:
Establish its accruals at the beginning of the year based on the certified list of collectibles on real property taxes as furnished by the Municipal Treasurer in compliance with Section 20 of the Manual on NGAS for LGUs, IPSAS 1 and P.D. No. 1445;
Investigate/trace the unreconciled differences, take appropriate actions by providing adjusting entries and monitor these accounts in order to prevent further discrepancies.  A copy of the adjusting entries, if any, shall be furnished to the Audit Team, for evaluation; and
Maintain the subsidiary ledgers of SET and RPT Receivables accounts including its corresponding Deferred SET and RPT accounts.

Implement the projects stipulated in the Agreement upon receipt of the funds from national agencies so that expected benefits will be achieved and delivered on time;

Retrieve the MOA, Trust Agreement, or Memorandum of Understanding to identify the SA to facilitate the immediate liquidation and return of the unused funds;

Return the unspent balances totaling ₱0.736 million to the SA or request approval from the SA to transfer the unexpended balance to the GF if the disposition thereof has not been provided in the MOA, Trust Agreement, or Memorandum of Understanding; and

Henceforth, add a column in the schedule of Due to NGAs for the date received and source agency to facilitate immediate implementation and return of the funds.

In order to comply with the provisions of RA 9003 and achieve the state’s policy that is to adopt a systematic, comprehensive and ecological solid waste management program we recommended that:

The Municipal Mayor request the Barangay Officials to allocate from their budget for the establishment, operation and maintenance of MRF in each barangay. It is also recommended that the Local Chief Executive request the Municipal Budget Officer to facilitate the inclusion of fund allocation for the full operation of the municipal MRF in succeeding budget proposals;

The MENRO facilitate the revision of the 10-year SWMP, submit to the EMB for approval and immediately commence implementation of such plans when approved;

All municipal employees act jointly such that the proposed sanitary landfill meet and pass the mandatory requirements. If this will be attained, the municipality will already have its own sanitary landfill and contract with other LGU for waste disposal will no longer be necessary, thus, cost for garbage disposal is expected to decrease;

The Management headed by the Chief Executive to strictly implement the Municipal Ordinance No. 253 series of 2005 known as the “Solid waste Segregation and Collection of Bantay, Ilocos Sur” to promote proper segregation of garbage; and

Intensify and sustain the current information drive and awareness campaign among the residents in coordination with the Barangay Officials on the implementation of the above-cited provisions under R.A. 9003 on preserving and protecting the environment.
